  "prompt": "How long does it take for ice also known as meth to get out of your system if you have been shooting it?",
  "response": "The time it takes for methamphetamine (commonly known as \"ice\") to clear from your system can vary based on several factors, including the frequency of use, the dosage, individual metabolism, overall health, and other personal factors.\n\nGenerally, methamphetamine can be detected in the following ways:\n\n- **Urine test**: Meth can typically be detected for 3 to 5 days after use, but in some cases, it might be detectable for a week or longer, especially with heavy or chronic use.\n- **Blood test**: Meth is usually detectable in the bloodstream for 1 to 3 days after use.\n- **Saliva test**: It can be detected for 1 to 4 days.\n- **Hair test**: Meth can be detected in hair follicles for up to 90 days or even longer, depending on hair length and growth rate.\n\nIf you have been shooting methamphetamine, it may have a more immediate and intense effect, but the clearance process is generally the same. If you or someone you know is struggling with substance use, seeking professional help is the best course of action.",
